### What problem does this feature solve?
When designing a `Customized Form Controls`, we may pass value or defaultValue with a simple structure, but build a complicated data structure inside the `Control`. Applying custom validators on the customized control like [the official sample](https://ant.design/components/form/#components-form-demo-customized-form-controls) does, we have no way to dig out the deep details inner, can't re-use some validation methods the `Customized Control` defined and it's hard to predicate the exposed `value` is valid.

The new convention, make it possible that every time we trigger changes, we feed the prop `validator` with error messages. Each form validation occurrence, form instance collect these error messages.
A variant of this convention is exposing `validator` property of `Customized Form Controls`, it will be call in validation occurrence through `ref` by form instance.

### What does the proposed API look like?
1. validator prop convention

```
class CustomizedControl extends React.Component {
    handleChange = (values) { // this values may be very complicated, but is parsed and easy to validate

        // this is a converter for changing inner values to external values. Certainly, we also have converter to handle outside 'value' and 'defaultValue'.
        const externalValues = this.converter(values)

        if (this.props.onChange) {
            this.props.onChange(externalValues) // externalValues is simple for submitting.
        }
        if (this.props.validator) {   // proposal here! feed errors to validator prop while changing

            // erro1Validator can easy validate innerValues
            const error1 = this.erro1Validator(values) || [] 
            const error2 = this.error2Validator(values) || []

            this.props.validator([error1, error2])
        }
    }
}
```

2. or a variant convention:

```
class CustomizedControl extends React.Component {
    validator = () => {  // proposal here! employ an instance method 'validator' or 'validate', return validation erros
        const error1 = this.erro1Validator(this.state.values) || []
        const error2 = this.error2Validator(this.state.values) || []

        return [error1, error2]
    }
}
```

